## Requirements outline

### **Functional requirements**

- [ ] Contains maps of at least 2 areas (north sydney and central coast) visualising a vast array of cheap places and local businesses for people to save money at.   
- [ ] Has a set of tips / ideas to save money for viewers to use so they can spend less and spend more on the things they want and need.   
- [ ] Has a suggestions box where people can submit places they want included on the app or can leave information on how expensive / cheap certain places are or want to leave their own tips for saving money  
- [ ] You can travel between the different branches of the website through buttons   
- [ ] The suggestions submitted by viewers is stored so I can access

### **Non-Functional requirements**

- [ ] Website itself looks aesthetically pleasing   
- [ ] Easy to navigate and go to the different sections of the website   
- [ ] Map of different places is easy to understand and apply to your own lifestyle  
- [ ] Tips are organised and look nice for viewers' ease.

# Testing and Evaluating

## Project Evaluation

Overall, I am very proud of my project, although it isn't absolutely perfect I have managed my time a lot better than other assessments and have put regular work in and have created a product I am pretty much satisfied with. It fulfills almost every requirement.

**contains a map of at least 2 areas** - Instead of using an image like I planned I had an interactable map of the whole world so I surpassed my criteria. 
Has a set of tips to save money - distinctly shown in the 'finance tips' although I would have liked to go deeper and put more effort into this part of the project If I had more time.

**Has a suggestions box** - Ideally it would have been a part of the actual site, but since I was running out of time I prioritised other parts of the project and made the applications box a link to a google form, still fulfilling this criteria. 

**The suggestions stored by viewers are stored** - Since I used google forms, this is still technically fulfilled.

**You can travel between different parts of the site through buttons** - the bar at the top of the site allows intuitive and easy movement between pages. 

**Site looks aesthetically pleasing** - I think I could improve on this part of my criteria as I don't think the site looks that good and seems a little outdated especially compared to my examples like uber and spotify, it still looks pretty good in my opinion. 

**Easy to navigate** - Since my site has a very accessible and intuitive navigation system using the bar at the top I think I fulfill this requirement. 

**Map of different places is easy to understand and apply to your own lifestyle** -
I think the map is pretty easy to understand, however I would have liked to have each marker be a different colour depending on its category.   

**Tips are organised and look nice for viewers' ease** - Although I didn't go in as much depth as I would have liked to for this section, the tips are still organised and easy to scroll through. 

In summary, I am very pleased with my progress on my site due to my regular progress and work I have put in and am satisfied with how it turned out, fulfilling most of my success criteria. There are some small things I would like to change like making different markers different colours, making the website look a bit more aesthetically pleasing, adding more places, making the google form a part of the actual website and going more in depth in the financial section. Despite these things I would do differently next time I'm still happy with how It ended up. One realisation I had mid way through making the project though is that my project overlaps with google maps a lot and is basically just a worse google maps and is less useful than I actually thought which I found demoralising. Future iterations could focus on affordability-specific filtering, which Google Maps does not emphasise.

## Social, Ethical & Legal Issues

### **Social Issues**
1. Equity of Access


My tool helps those under financial pressure, but people without internet access, smartphones, or digital literacy may be excluded. 


2. Accuracy and Reliability


If location data or prices are outdated, users may waste time or feel misled. This can damage trust in the project.


3. Community Impact


Highlighting ‚Äúcheap‚Äù places could benefit local communities by increasing foot traffic to affordable stores. However, it could also disadvantage small businesses not included in your dataset, creating perceptions of bias.


### **Ethical Issues**
1. Data Integrity and Responsibility


I need to follow the ethical obligation to ensure that the advice (In the finance tips section) is responsible, evidence-based, and does not mislead users because inaccurate advice could cause financial harm.


2. Privacy and Safety


Currently, I need to make sure I keep the viewers names and emails in the google form private and If I eventually add geolocation (‚Äúnear me‚Äù functionality), I would need to ensure that users‚Äô location data is handled responsibly, not stored or misused.


### **Legal Issues**
1. Consumer Law


Technically since my financial advice is presented as professional guidance without disclaimers, I am technically breaking Australian consumer law. And I should probably have included a disclaimer that the tips are general information.


2. Intellectual Property


The map relies on Leaflet and possibly other datasets (like OpenStreetMap or business directories). One issue is that I ensure compliance with their licensing terms (e.g., attribution requirements).


1. Defamation and Accuracy


If I incorrectly list something as ‚Äúcheap‚Äù or if errors imply bad things about businesses, legal disputes could arise. Ensuring information is verifiable and up to date reduces this risk.
